"# Chapter 6 — Sprite grid

The sprite grid is the composer's pixel editor. It lets a person paint on a fixed-size grid of cells, each holding a palette index. The emitted form is a 2D list of numbers — no PNG, no binary blob, no proprietary format. Every pixel is a number in a list. Open the file, read the numbers, understand the sprite.

## 6.1 The verb signature

```
(composer/sprite-grid :bind :size . options)
```

- `:bind` — path. Where the sprite's target form writes.
- `:size` — pair like `'(16 . 16)`. Width and height in pixels.
- `:palette` — symbol, optional. The palette to use. Default `'pico-8`.
- `:emit-shape` — symbol, optional. `'sprite/from-grid` or `'sprite/from-pixels`. Default `'sprite/from-grid`.
- `:tools` — list of tool symbols, optional. Which tools the surface offers.

## 6.2 The emitted target form

A sprite emits as:

```
(sprite/from-grid (quote ((0 0 0 8 8 0 0 0)
                          (0 0 8 8 8 8 0 0)
                          (0 8 8 8 8 8 8 0)
                          (8 8 8 8 8 8 8 8)
                          (8 8 8 8 8 8 8 8)
                          (0 8 8 8 8 8 8 0)
                          (0 0 8 8 8 8 0 0)
                          (0 0 0 8 8 0 0 0))))
```

An 8x8 sprite. Each row is a list of eight palette indices. Zero is transparent by convention. Non-zero indices reference the palette named in the widget's `:palette` option.

The widget declaration emitted at the canvas level captures the widget's construction:

```
(composer/sprite-grid :bind (quote (cart/sprites :hero))
                      :size (quote (16 . 16))
                      :palette (quote pico-8))
```

Just the declaration. The pixels themselves live in the target form the widget writes.

## 6.3 ASCII mockup — an 8x8 sprite

Motoi's TUI renderer draws sprites as ASCII with palette indices as characters (0='.', 1-9=digits, 10-15=a-f). Here is a small ball sprite:

```
sprite: cart/sprites/hero (8x8, palette pico-8)
  ...88...
  ..8888..
  .888888.
  88888888
  88888888
  .888888.
  ..8888..
  ...88...
```

Same shape as the emitted form above. Each `8` is palette index 8 (red in pico-8). Each `.` is index 0 (transparent).

## 6.4 The HTML-16 palette

Composer v1.1 added a named-color palette called `'html-16`. It contains 16 named CSS colors chosen for legibility and pleasant balance:

```
01:black       02:white       03:crimson    04:forestgreen
05:peachpuff   06:gold        07:coral      08:plum
09:teal        10:sienna      11:pink       12:skyblue
13:khaki       14:lavender    15:mediumseagreen  16:saddlebrown
```

Verified: `(color/palette-html-16)` returns this list of 16 symbols. `(color/named 'crimson)` returns `\"#dc143c\"`.

Use the html-16 palette when you want your sprite to reference colors by name instead of by index. A sprite bound to a palette of named colors is human-parseable in a way an index-only sprite is not.

The default is still `'pico-8` because kids who grew up with fantasy consoles expect it. Both palettes are available; pick per widget.

## 6.5 Size

`:size '(w . h)` sets the pixel dimensions. Common sizes:

- `'(8 . 8)` — the classic fantasy-console tile size.
- `'(16 . 16)` — a common character sprite.
- `'(32 . 32)` — larger characters or props.

The widget stores width and height as the first and second elements of the pair. `size '(8 . 8)` gives an 8x8 grid. `size '(24 . 16)` gives a wide rectangle.

## 6.6 Pixels start blank

The widget initializes with all pixels set to palette index 0 — transparent by convention. Every cell is `.` in the TUI, or fully see-through in a graphical surface. Kids paint by clicking cells with the pen tool.

## 6.7 The tools option

`:tools` accepts a list of tool symbols the surface should expose:

```scheme
:tools '(pen fill line rect circle)
```

Legal tools include pen (paint one pixel), fill (flood fill), line (draw a straight line), rect (rectangle), circle (circle), lasso (select region), and eraser (paint index 0).

Not every surface honors every tool. The v1.1 TUI shows only the current pixels, not a tool palette; a full Curator canvas renders the tool bank as icons.

## 6.8 A verified example

```scheme
(composer/sprite-grid :bind '(cart/sprites :hero)
                      :size '(16 . 16)
                      :palette 'pico-8)
```

Emit in a canvas:

```
(composer/canvas (:bind (quote (cart/sprites)))
  (composer/sprite-grid :bind (quote (cart/sprites :hero))
                        :size (quote (16 . 16))
                        :palette (quote pico-8)))
```

The widget declaration emits the size as `'(16 . 16)` and palette as `'pico-8`. Reload and the widget reconstructs at 16x16 on the pico-8 palette.

The pixel data itself (the 2D list) is written to `(cart/sprites :hero)` at edit time. To emit the pixel data you would need to look at the target form the widget wrote to, not the canvas emit.

## 6.9 Palette per sprite

A palette is a property of the widget. Different sprites in the same cart can use different palettes:

```scheme
(composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/sprites))
  (composer/sprite-grid :bind '(cart/sprites :hero)
                        :size '(16 . 16)
                        :palette 'pico-8)
  (composer/sprite-grid :bind '(cart/sprites :sky)
                        :size '(32 . 32)
                        :palette 'html-16))
```

Two sprites. Hero uses pico-8's palette (16 fantasy-console colors). Sky uses html-16's palette (16 named CSS colors). Both save side by side in the same file.

## 6.10 Palette index zero — transparency

By convention, palette index 0 is transparent. The runtime treats index-0 cells as see-through when compositing sprites. This is why the ASCII mockup shows `.` for index 0 — visually the background is `nothing`.

If a sprite needs a solid background, use a different index. Kids doing background-fill tricks often paint the whole grid to a solid color (say index 12, sky blue) and then paint character pixels on top. The sprite is opaque because no cells are 0.

## 6.11 Emit-shape

`:emit-shape` picks the head symbol of the target form. Two legal values:

- `'sprite/from-grid` — default. Emits a 2D list of palette indices.
- `'sprite/from-pixels` — Emits a flat list of `(x y color)` triples.

The from-grid shape is nicer for hand-editing (each row on its own line). The from-pixels shape is compact when a sprite is sparse (few non-transparent pixels).

## 6.12 A worked cart

`carts/composer/sprite-editor.slat` shows a sprite grid, text field, color picker, and a couple of buttons:

```scheme
(define editor
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(sprites))
    (composer/text-field :bind '(sprites :name) :label \"sprite name\" :value \"hero\")
    (composer/sprite-grid :bind '(sprites :hero) :size '(8 . 8) :palette 'pico-8)
    (composer/color-picker :bind '(sprites :ink) :palette 'pico-8)
    (composer/toggle :bind '(sprites :grid) :label \"show grid\" :value #t)
    (composer/button :label \"Clear\" :emits '(sprite/clear (quote hero)))
    (composer/button :label \"Save\"  :emits '(sprite/save (quote hero)))))
```

Six children. Text field for the sprite's name. Sprite grid at 8x8 with pico-8 palette. Color picker for the current ink. Toggle for grid overlay. Clear and Save buttons.

Run this cart and the canvas emit shows all six children with current state. Save the emit to disk. Reload. Everything reconstructs.

## 6.13 What to remember from this chapter

- Sprite grid holds a 2D grid of palette indices and emits them as a 2D list.
- `:size '(w . h)` — the pixel dimensions.
- `:palette 'pico-8` or `'html-16` — the palette by name.
- `:tools '(pen fill line rect circle)` — which tools the surface offers.
- Palette index 0 is transparent by convention.
- The emit-shape is `'sprite/from-grid` (2D list) or `'sprite/from-pixels` (flat triples). Default from-grid.
- The v1.1 HTML-16 palette gives you 16 named colors legible by their CSS names.

Chapter 7 introduces the tile map — a grid of tile IDs that becomes a level.
")
